Orchestrates the four CTX CLI-level operations (`scan_run`, `check_run`,
`prune_run`, `update_run`) over `ctx-summarize`'s generic walk/summarize
machinery, wiring in the real filesystem (`StdFs`) and hash-tree logic
from `crate::hash`. This is the layer where "what runs when" is decided;
the actual leaf/rollup summarization mechanics live in `ctx-summarize`.

Key asymmetry: prompts are loaded from `prompts_dir` resolved against the
process cwd via `load_prompts`, independent of `base` (the scan target) —
a scan target need not carry CTX's own prompt files. `summarize` (the
generic, testable core) takes pre-loaded `Prompts` and calls
`summ::scope_check` before doing any work, so approval gating happens
before summarization, not after.

`update_run` is the most delicate: it computes staleness once, prunes
orphans unconditionally (pure filesystem, no model call), then only
loads prompts/calls the model if `stale.needs_regeneration()` is true.
A tree stale purely from orphan artifacts prunes and returns without
touching prompts or the agent. `regenerate` assumes `stale.stale_dirs` is
already deepest-first ordered by `hash::diff` — it doesn't re-sort.

`check_run` and the staleness computation in `update_run` both call
`reconcile::find_orphan_artifacts` and then narrow via
`scan.artifacts_excluding(&stale.orphan_leaves)` to avoid double-counting
leaves that are both hash-stale and structurally orphaned — this
narrowing logic is duplicated between the two functions and must be kept
in sync if `Staleness`'s orphan fields change shape.

All four public entry points construct their own `StdFs::new(base...)`
and call `walker::walk_dir(base)` independently — no shared walk cache
across calls in one process.